    en: "Chili is one of the Monroe County towns that licenses plumbers at the local level rather than relying on a third-party or statewide credential. Plumbers working in Chili have to hold a Chili Master Plumber license specifically — a Rochester Examining Board of Plumbers certificate does not transfer to Chili.\n\nChili Master Plumber license requirements. A plumber applies to the town directly. The application requires proof of NY Department of Labor apprenticeship and journeyman experience (or equivalent), a current general liability insurance policy that names the Town of Chili as an additional insured, and workers' compensation coverage under Workers' Compensation Law 10. Licenses are issued by the Town Building Department and run on an annual renewal. A license that goes five consecutive years without renewal is revoked and requires a new application.\n\nReciprocity. Chili does not publish a reciprocity list for other Monroe County plumber licenses. A plumber licensed in Rochester city, Brockport village, or another municipality still has to apply for a Chili license separately to pull permits inside Chili.\n\nSeparate plumbing permit. The plumbing permit is a separate form from the general building permit. Chili uses the CloudPermit online portal for plumbing applications. This is the same portal many Monroe County municipalities use, so a plumber with existing credentials can submit a Chili application through the same system.\n\nWhen a permit is required. Water heater replacement, new fixtures (sinks, toilets, tubs, showers), sewer lateral work, water service line work, adding a bathroom, new drain-waste-vent or water-supply piping, and any gas piping from the meter to an appliance all require a plumbing permit. Small like-for-like repairs — swapping a single faucet or valve — generally do not.\n\nHomeowner self-work. Chili explicitly allows homeowners to do like-for-like fixture or appliance swaps on an owner-occupied single-family home. The homeowner still pulls the permit and passes inspection. Moving a fixture, changing the plumbing layout, adding a new bathroom, or touching the service line is not allowed as homeowner work; those scopes require a Chili-licensed plumber.\n\nInspection flow. After the work is complete, a town inspector performs the plumbing inspection. Chili uses in-house inspectors rather than third-party agencies. Inspections typically occur at rough-in (before walls are closed up) and at final.\n\nGas piping is plumbing. Gas piping from the meter to any appliance (furnace, water heater, range, dryer) is plumbing work in Chili. An HVAC contractor replacing a furnace needs to coordinate with a Chili-licensed plumber for the gas line; the HVAC contractor cannot pull the plumbing permit.\n\nEnforcement. Unlicensed plumbing work in Chili is a code violation. Permit denials and enforcement actions against the contractor can follow. Work done without a permit can also affect insurance coverage on the property.\n\nState protections. Wage theft protections (Labor Law 191 and 193), the Scaffold Law for elevated work (Labor Law 240 and 241(6)), mechanic's liens (Lien Law 3 and 10), and General Business Law 349 for deceptive home-improvement practices apply in Chili as statewide. The statewide plumbing-residential-ny entry covers those layers."
